In Sat. xiii. 17 he speaks of Calvinus, the friend he addresses, ast then sixty years old, aud born iu the consulship of Fonteius. I·think it almost certain that the consul referred to is L. The earlier date to which Lipsius aud others refer it, as stated in my note (xiii. 17), is sowy-seven years belbre the reign of Hadrian. Either, therefore, Juvenal did not write at all in that reign, or this Satira was written while Hadrian was emperor, about no. 119. Otherwise Juvenal's Satires must range over a period of fifty years or thereabouts, and one of the very best must have been nearly the earliest. Those who are of opinion that the allusion to Meroe in v. 163 of this Satira, resulted from personal observation, must be prepared to admit the later date, or to suppose that the banishment of Juvenal to Egypt by Domitian is altogether fabulous, aud that his visit to that country must hare been early in the reign of Vespasian‚ if not before it, since the Satire, according to the other hypothesis, must hare been written about the fourth year of that reign, and nine years before Domitian became emperor.
